Trees

One dimensional \(X\)

data("Boston")

n <- nrow(Boston)
n_train <- floor(0.8*n)
n_test <- n - n_train

idx_test <- sample(1:n, n_test, replace = F)
Boston_ts <- Boston[idx_test,]
Boston <- Boston[-idx_test,]

xgrid <- seq(min(Boston$lstat), max(Boston$lstat), length.out = 1000)


big_tree <- rpart(medv ~ lstat, method = "anova", data = Boston,
                  control = rpart.control(minsplit = 5, cp = .0005))
cat('size of big tree:', length(unique(big_tree$where)), '\n')
size of big tree: 81 
# Plot the cv error curve for the tree
par(mar=c(4,4,2,2), family = 'serif')
plotcp(big_tree)

# Pick the best Cp
bestcp <- big_tree$cptable[which.min(big_tree$cptable[,"xerror"]),"CP"]
cat('bestcp:', bestcp, '\n')
bestcp: 0.005103786 
# Prune the tree down to that Cp
best_tree <- prune(big_tree, cp = bestcp)
cat('size of best tree:', length(unique(best_tree$where)), '\n')
size of best tree: 7 
# Show the optimal tree
rpart.plot(best_tree, clip.right.labs = FALSE, under = TRUE, digits = 4)

Show suboptimal trees

cpvec <- c(0.1, bestcp, 3E-3)
par(mfrow=c(3,2), mar = c(2,2,2,2), family = 'serif')
for(i in 1:3){
  plot(Boston$lstat, Boston$medv, pch = 16, cex = .5, 
       xlab = 'lstat', ylab = 'medv')
  ptree <- prune(big_tree, cp = cpvec[i])
  pred <- as.numeric(predict(ptree, newdata = list(lstat = xgrid)))
  lines(xgrid, pred, col = 'red', lwd = 2)
  title(paste('alpha =',round(cpvec[i],4)))
  rpart.plot(ptree, clip.right.labs = FALSE, under = TRUE, digits = 4)
}

# Prediction on the test set
err_1D <- (as.numeric(predict(best_tree, newdata = Boston_ts)) - 
             Boston_ts$medv)^2

Esemble methods

Bagging and Random forests

library(randomForest)

ntreev <- c(100,500,1000)
nset <- length(ntreev)
y_hat <- array(NA, dim = c(n_test, nset))
set.seed(123)
for(i in 1:nset){
  rffit <- randomForest(medv ~ ., data = Boston, ntree = ntreev[i], maxnodes = 25)
  y_hat[,i] <- predict(rffit, newdata = Boston_ts)
}

err_RF <- (y_hat[,3] - Boston_ts$medv)^2

Boosting

library(gbm)

gbm_fit <- gbm(medv ~ ., distribution = "gaussian", data = Boston,
               n.trees = 5000, interaction.depth = 1, shrinkage = 0.001, 
               cv.folds = 5)  

gbm.perf(gbm_fit, method = "cv")

gbm_fit <- gbm(medv ~ ., distribution = "gaussian", data = Boston,
               n.trees = 10000, interaction.depth = 1, shrinkage = 0.01, 
               cv.folds = 5)  

gbm.perf(gbm_fit, method = "cv")

[1] 3937
hyper_grid <- expand.grid(
  shrinkage = c(.001, .01, .1),
  interaction.depth = c(1, 2, 5),
  n.minobsinnode = c(5, 10, 15),
  optimal_trees = 0,
  min_RMSE = 0
)

# total number of combinations
nrow(hyper_grid)
[1] 27
# grid search 
for(i in 1:nrow(hyper_grid)) {
  # reproducibility
  set.seed(123)
  
  gbm_fit <- gbm(medv ~ ., distribution = "gaussian", data = Boston,
                 n.trees = 10000, 
                 interaction.depth = hyper_grid$interaction.depth[i], 
                 shrinkage = hyper_grid$shrinkage[i], 
                 n.minobsinnode = hyper_grid$n.minobsinnode[i],
                 cv.folds = 5)
  
  # add min training error and trees to grid
  hyper_grid$optimal_trees[i] <- which.min(gbm_fit$cv.error)
  hyper_grid$min_RMSE[i] <- sqrt(min(gbm_fit$cv.error))
}

opt_hypers <- hyper_grid %>% 
  dplyr::arrange(min_RMSE) %>%
  head(10)

# train GBM model
gbm_fit_final <- gbm(medv ~ ., distribution = "gaussian", data = Boston,
                     n.trees = 5000, 
                     interaction.depth = opt_hypers$interaction.depth[1], 
                     shrinkage = opt_hypers$shrinkage[1], 
                     n.minobsinnode = opt_hypers$n.minobsinnode[1],
                     cv.folds = 5)

gbm.perf(gbm_fit_final, method = "cv")

[1] 4056
y_hat <- predict(gbm_fit_final, newdata = Boston_ts, 
                 n.trees = which.min(gbm_fit_final$cv.error))

err_boost <- (y_hat - Boston_ts$medv)^2

errors <- melt(cbind('Tree 1' = err_1D,
